Rescue teams in northern Mozambique are helping people who've been trapped by rapidly rising floodwater. Torrential rains continue since Cyclone Kenneth hit last week. PEMBA - Rescue teams in northern Mozambique are helping people who've been trapped by rapidly rising floodwater.
Torrential rains lashed parts of the country after Cyclone Kenneth hit last week, causing serious flooding in some areas. READ: Mozambique braces for floods after Cyclone Kenneth Authorities expect the floods to worsen. The storm slammed into the province of Cabo Delgado on Thursday, killing five people. It has since pounded an area prone to floods and landslides, fuelling fears rivers could burst their banks and leave vast areas under water. READ: Fears as death toll rises in cyclone-hit Mozambique The storm comes just six weeks after Cyclone Idai battered the port city of Beira. At least 1,000 people were killed across Mozambique, Malawi and Zimbabwe.